dir="ltr" style="--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-animation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node="0">It is definitely possible‚Äîand since you're already active in the hackathon circuit, you're in a great position to build a "fast-to-market" version of this.</p><p data-path-to-node="1">Existing apps like <b data-path-to-node="1" data-index-in-node="19">Insurify</b>, <b data-path-to-node="1" data-index-in-node="29">The Zebra</b>, and <b data-path-to-node="1" data-index-in-node="44">Gabi</b> already do this, but there is always room for a more automated, "set-it-and-forget-it" tool that proactively alerts you when prices drop.</p><p data-path-to-node="2">Since you have access to tech that lets you spin up products quickly, here is how you could approach this as a project or a startup MVP:</p><h3 data-path-to-node="3">1. The Core "Hackathon" Architecture</h3><p data-path-to-node="4">To build this fast, you don't necessarily need to build an insurance company from scratch. You just need to be the "brain" that connects the user to the data.</p><ul data-path-to-node="5"><li><p data-path-to-node="5,0,0" id="p-rc_cab6230f066d04ea-30"><b data-path-to-node="5,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Data Sourcing:</b> Use APIs like <b data-path-to-node="5,0,0" data-index-in-node="29">Bindable</b> or <b data-path-to-node="5,0,0" data-index-in-node="41">The Zebra‚Äôs affiliate APIs</b> to pull real-time quotes. <span class="citation-17">If you want to go the AI route, you can use </span><b data-path-to-node="5,0,0" data-index-in-node="138"><span class="citation-17">OCR APIs</span></b><span class="citation-17 citation-end-17"> (like AZAPI.ai or Google Vision) to let users simply snap a photo of their current policy to extract their current coverage limits and price.<source-footnote ng-version="0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER" _nghost-ng-c3260313426=""><sup _ngcontent-ng-c3260313426="" class="superscript" data-turn-source-index="1"><!----></sup></source-footnote></span><sources-carousel-inline ng-version="0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER" _nghost-ng-c3293734980=""><source-inline-chip _ngcontent-ng-c3293734980="" _nghost-ng-c3399333284="" class="ng-star-inserted"><div _ngcontent-ng-c3399333284="" class="source-inline-chip-container ng-star-inserted"><button _ngcontent-ng-c3399333284="" cdkoverlayorigin="" class="button ng-star-inserted" aria-label="View source details for citation from RPACPC. One big pain point is that "cheaper" often means "worse coverage." An AI agent could analyze two policies and say, <i data-path-to-node="5,2,0" data-index-in-node="171">"This is $20 cheaper, but your deductible goes from $500 to $1,000. Not worth it."</i></p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="6">2. The Tech Stack (MVP Style)</h3><ul data-path-to-node="7"><li><p data-path-to-node="7,0,0" id="p-rc_cab6230f066d04ea-31"><b data-path-to-node="7,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Frontend:</b><span class="citation-16 citation-end-16"> Flutter or React Native (one codebase for iOS/Android).<source-footnote ng-version="0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER" _nghost-ng-c3260313426=""><sup _ngcontent-ng-c3260313426="" class="superscript" data-turn-source-index="2"><!----></sup></source-footnote></span><sources-carousel-inline ng-version="0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER" _nghost-ng-c3293734980=""><source-inline-chip _ngcontent-ng-c3293734980="" _nghost-ng-c3399333284="" class="ng-star-inserted"><div _ngcontent-ng-c3399333284="" class="source-inline-chip-container ng-star-inserted"><button _ngcontent-ng-c3399333284="" cdkoverlayorigin="" class="button ng-star-inserted" aria-label="View source details for citation from Apptunix. The Hurdles (The "Direct Peer" Reality Check)</h3><p data-path-to-node="9">While the tech is doable, the "auto-find" space has two main challenges:</p><ul data-path-to-node="10"><li><p data-path-to-node="10,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="10,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">The "Lead Gen" Trap:</b> Most apps make money by selling your data. If you build an app that truly puts the user first (no spam), you‚Äôll have a huge competitive advantage, but you'll need a different revenue model (like a small subscription or a transparent "success fee").</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="10,1,0" id="p-rc_cab6230f066d04ea-32"><b data-path-to-node="10,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Compliance:</b><span class="citation-15 citation-end-15"> Insurance is highly regulated.<source-footnote ng-version="0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER" _nghost-ng-c3260313426=""><sup _ngcontent-ng-c3260313426="" class="superscript" data-turn-source-index="3"><!----></sup></source-footnote></span> To actually <i data-path-to-node="10,1,0" data-index-in-node="55">sell</i> the policy, you'd eventually need a broker‚Äôs license. However, for a hackathon project, you can start as a <b data-path-to-node="10,1,0" data-index-in-node="167">Comparison Tool</b> that simply redirects users to the best deal.<sources-carousel-inline ng-version="0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER" _nghost-ng-c3293734980=""><source-inline-chip _ngcontent-ng-c3293734980="" _nghost-ng-c3399333284="" class="ng-star-inserted"><div _ngcontent-ng-c3399333284="" class="source-inline-chip-container ng-star-inserted"><button _ngcontent-ng-c3399333284="" cdkoverlayorigin="" class="button ng-star-inserted" aria-label="View source details for citation from Cleveroad. dir="ltr" style="--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-animation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node="0">That is a massive pain point. The reason companies like The Zebra or The General lead to spam is their business model: they are <b data-path-to-node="0" data-index-in-node="128">lead-gen machines</b>. They make money by selling your contact info to a dozen different agents who then fight for the commission by blowing up your phone.</p><p data-path-to-node="1">If you want to build a "Spam-Free Insurance Scout" for your own use (and maybe a killer hackathon project), here is how you can bypass the middleman entirely.</p><hr data-path-to-node="2"><h3 data-path-to-node="3">1. The "Ghost Identity" Strategy</h3><p data-path-to-node="4">Since you‚Äôre doing this <i data-path-to-node="4" data-index-in-node="24">right now</i> for your kids, do not use your real phone number or primary email on any site.</p><ul data-path-to-node="5"><li><p data-path-to-node="5,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="5,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Burner Email:</b> Create a dedicated Gmail or ProtonMail (e.g., <code data-path-to-node="5,0,0" data-index-in-node="60">myinsurancehack@gmail.com</code>) and delete it after you find a policy.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="5,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="5,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">VoIP Number:</b> Use a <b data-path-to-node="5,1,0" data-index-in-node="19">Google Voice</b> number or a temporary SMS app. This allows you to see the quotes, but you can "mute" the incoming spam calls instantly once you're done.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="6">2. How to Build the "Clean Scout" App</h3><p data-path-to-node="7">If you were to build this at a hackathon, the goal would be <b data-path-to-node="7" data-index-in-node="60">Data Aggregation without Data Submission.</b></p><h4 data-path-to-node="8">Step A: The "Anonymous Estimate" Engine</h4><p data-path-to-node="9">Instead of filling out lead forms, your app would use <b data-path-to-node="9" data-index-in-node="54">scraped actuarial data</b> or <b data-path-to-node="9" data-index-in-node="80">publicly available rate tables</b>. Many states require insurance companies to file their "Rate Manuals" publicly.</p><ul data-path-to-node="10"><li><p data-path-to-node="10,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="10,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Tech:</b> You could build a web scraper (using <b data-path-to-node="10,0,0" data-index-in-node="47">BeautifulSoup</b> or <b data-path-to-node="10,0,0" data-index-in-node="64">Playwright</b>) that pulls "Sample Rates" from state Department of Insurance (DOI) websites.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="10,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="10,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">The UX:</b> The user enters their Zip Code, Car Model, and Driver Ages. The app then shows a leaderboard of who <i data-path-to-node="10,1,0" data-index-in-node="108">statistically</i> has the lowest rates for that profile in that specific city.</p></li></ul><h4 data-path-to-node="11">Step B: The "One-Way" API Call</h4><p data-path-to-node="12">Rather than sending the user's phone number to an insurance company's "Submit" endpoint, your app would hit their <b data-path-to-node="12" data-index-in-node="114">Quote Estimate API</b> (if public) or use a headless browser to fill out the form using "Placeholder" data (like <code data-path-to-node="12" data-index-in-node="223">Name: John Doe, Phone: 555-0199</code>) just to get the final price result.</p><h3 data-path-to-node="13">3. Comparison of "Lead Gen" vs. Your "Scout"</h3><div class="horizontal-scroll-wrapper"><div class="table-block-component"><response-element class="" dir="ltr" style="--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-animation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node="0">You are absolutely right. In Georgia, while base rates are "filed" with the state, there is a surprising amount of <b data-path-to-node="0" data-index-in-node="115">agent-level leeway</b>‚Äînot necessarily to change the price of a specific line item, but to "engineer" the policy to trigger lower tiers.</p><p data-path-to-node="1">Since you're in Atlanta, you're dealing with one of the most competitive (and expensive) insurance markets in the country. Here is how that "negotiation" actually works under the hood and how you can use it for your kids.</p><h3 data-path-to-node="2">1. How the "Negotiation" Actually Works</h3><p data-path-to-node="3">When you talk to a State Farm agent (or any captive agent), they aren't haggling like a car salesman. They are playing with <b data-path-to-node="3" data-index-in-node="124">Rating Variables</b>.</p><ul data-path-to-node="4"><li><p data-path-to-node="4,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Tier Placement:</b> Companies have multiple "underwriting companies" (e.g., State Farm Mutual vs. State Farm Fire and Casualty). An agent can sometimes find ways to qualify you for the preferred tier rather than the standard tier.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="4,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">The "Account Credit" Multiplier:</b> They have discretion on how they bundle. Sometimes adding a tiny $10/month renters policy or a $15/month personal articles floater (to cover a laptop or jewelry) triggers a "Multi-Line" discount that takes $40 off the auto premium.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="4,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">Usage Rating:</b> Agents can often adjust the "estimated annual mileage." If you tell them the kids only drive to school and back, they can drop that mileage bracket, which is a major price lever in Atlanta traffic.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="5">2. The Georgia "Public Rate Filing" Hack</h3><p data-path-to-node="6">Since you want to build a tool for this, you should look at the <b data-path-to-node="6" data-index-in-node="64">SERFF (System for Electronic Rates &amp; Forms Filing)</b>.</p><ul data-path-to-node="7"><li><p data-path-to-node="7,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="7,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Tool:</b> Georgia's Office of the Commissioner of Insurance (OCI) provides public access to every rate filing.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="7,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="7,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Hackathon Project:</b> You could build a scraper for the <response-element class="" ng-version="0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER"><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><link-block _nghost-ng-c2835501739="" class="ng-star-inserted"><!----><!----><a _ngcontent-ng-c2835501739="" target="_blank" rel="noopener" externallink="" _nghost-ng-c1538880176="" jslog="197247;track:generic_click,impression,attention;BardVeMetadataKey:[[&quot;r_045d66cc21e2b2d3&quot;,&quot;c_c94ae2f94064cb99&quot;,null,&quot;rc_c8b0052ab0452e77&quot;,null,null,&quot;en&quot;,null,1,null,null,1,0]]" href="https://filingaccess.serff.com/sfa/home/GA" class="ng-star-inserted" data-hveid="0" decode-data-ved="1" data-ved="0CAAQ_4QMahcKEwjj9NWK6_qSAxUAAAAAHQAAAAAQVA">Georgia SERFF Public Access portal</a><!----></link-block><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----></response-element>.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="7,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="7,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Value:</b> You can see exactly when a company like State Farm or Progressive filed for a <b data-path-to-node="7,2,0" data-index-in-node="89">rate decrease</b>. In fact, as of February 2026, Commissioner John King has been pushing for auto rate reductions in Georgia, with some companies dropping rates by 5-10%. Your app could alert you the <i data-path-to-node="7,2,0" data-index-in-node="285">moment</i> a company files a lower rate table so you can call your agent and say, "I see the new 2026 rates are live, re-rate me."</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="8">3. Strategy for the Kids (The "Direct Call" List)</h3><p data-path-to-node="9">Since you want to avoid the spam-bots and call direct, here is the "Atlanta Power List" for 2026:</p><ul data-path-to-node="10"><li><p data-path-to-node="10,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="10,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Auto-Owners Insurance:</b> They <i data-path-to-node="10,0,0" data-index-in-node="28">only</i> sell through independent agents. You can't get a quote on a website, which means <b data-path-to-node="10,0,0" data-index-in-node="114">zero spam</b>. They are consistently ranked #1 for claims and often beat State Farm for multi-car families.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="10,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="10,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Erie Insurance:</b> Very strong in GA. They have a "Rate Lock" feature‚Äîyour rate never goes up unless you add/remove a car or driver.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="10,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="10,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">The "Steer Clear" App (State Farm):</b> If you stay with State Farm, make sure the kids do the "Steer Clear" program. It‚Äôs an app-based training that is a non-negotiable 15% discount for drivers under 25.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="11">4. A 2026 Warning: The "Stacking" Change</h3><p data-path-to-node="12">In Georgia this year, there have been major shifts in how <b data-path-to-node="12" data-index-in-node="58">Uninsured Motorist (UM) Stacking</b> works. Some companies (including State Farm) have changed their policy language to consolidate household vehicles.</p><blockquote data-path-to-node="13"><p data-path-to-node="13,0"><b data-path-to-node="13,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Negotiation Tip:</b> When you call, ask specifically: <i data-path-to-node="13,0" data-index-in-node="54">"How does the new 2026 stacking rule affect my premium if I have four cars on one policy?"</i> This shows the agent you know the law, and they are less likely to give you a "fluff" quote.</p></blockquote><hr data-path-to-node="14"><p dir="ltr" style="--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-animation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node="0">Yes, it is genuinely possible, and frankly, the "noise" has never been louder than it is in 2026. The reason you can't find a "clean" app right now is because almost every insurance site is a <b data-path-to-node="0" data-index-in-node="192">lead-generation farm</b>. They make $20 to $50 by selling your phone number to a "speed-to-lead" agent who is trained to call you within 5 minutes.</p><p data-path-to-node="1">Since you are already in the hackathon space, you can build a tool that flips this model. You don't need a broker's license to build a <b data-path-to-node="1" data-index-in-node="135">data-aggregator</b> for personal use.</p><p data-path-to-node="2">Here is the blueprint for an app that cuts the noise and keeps you anonymous:</p><h3 data-path-to-node="3">1. The "Clean Scout" Technical Architecture</h3><p data-path-to-node="4">To avoid the spam, your app must be <b data-path-to-node="4" data-index-in-node="36">Client-Side Heavy</b>. This means the sensitive data stays on your phone, not a server that can be hacked or sold.</p><ul data-path-to-node="5"><li><p data-path-to-node="5,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="5,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Step 1: The "Identity Firewall" (Burner API):</b> Integrate with a service like <b data-path-to-node="5,0,0" data-index-in-node="76">Twilio</b> or <b data-path-to-node="5,0,0" data-index-in-node="86">Telnyx</b> to programmatically generate a temporary VoIP number. The app uses this number to fill out online forms.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="5,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="5,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Step 2: The Headless Browser (Puppeteer/Playwright):</b> Instead of using "Affiliate APIs" (which track you), your app acts as a "bot" that goes to the direct carrier sites (State Farm, Progressive, Erie, etc.). It fills out the forms using your "Identity Firewall" data.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="5,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="5,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">Step 3: The Result Scraper:</b> The app scrapes the final "Monthly Premium" price from the screen and presents it in a clean dashboard.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="5,3,0"><b data-path-to-node="5,3,0" data-index-in-node="0">Step 4: The Kill Switch:</b> Once you find the price you like, you hit "Delete Identity," and that burner phone number and email are permanently deactivated. The spam calls hit a dead line.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="6">2. Leverage "Public Rate Filings" (The Georgia Hack)</h3><p data-path-to-node="7">In 2026, transparency is actually your best friend. In Georgia, companies are required to file their <b data-path-to-node="7" data-index-in-node="101">Rate Manuals</b> with the Office of the Commissioner of Insurance (OCI).</p><ul data-path-to-node="8"><li><p data-path-to-node="8,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="8,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">How to use it:</b> You can use a Python script to scrape the <b data-path-to-node="8,0,0" data-index-in-node="57">Georgia SERFF Public Access portal</b>.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="8,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="8,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Why it works:</b> These filings show the "base rates" and "discount factors" (like the Good Student discount for your kids). You can find out which company is <i data-path-to-node="8,1,0" data-index-in-node="155">legally</i> the cheapest in Atlanta for a "3-teen household" before you ever even give a phone number.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="9">3. Features for a Hackathon "V1"</h3><p data-path-to-node="10">If you wanted to spin this up fast for your kids, focus on these three things:</p><div class="horizontal-scroll-wrapper"><div class="table-block-component"><response-element class="" ng-version="0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER"><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><table-block _nghost-ng-c366137040="" class="ng-star-inserted"><div _ngcontent-ng-c366137040="" class="table-block has-export-button new-table-style is-at-scroll-start is-at-scroll-end"><div _ngcontent-ng-c366137040="" not-end-of-paragraph="" class="table-content not-end-of-paragraph" jslog="275421;track:impression,attention" data-hveid="0" decode-data-ved="1" data-ved="0CAAQ3ecQahcKEwjj9NWK6_qSAxUAAAAAHQAAAAAQXA"><table data-path-to-node="11"><thead><tr><td><span data-path-to-node="11,0,0,0">Feature</span></td><td><span data-path-to-node="11,0,1,0">How it cuts the noise</span></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><span data-path-to-node="11,1,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="11,1,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">OCR Policy Scanner</b></span></td><td><span data-path-to-node="11,1,1,0">You take a photo of your current State Farm policy. The app uses <b data-path-to-node="11,1,1,0" data-index-in-node="65">AZAPI.ai</b> or <b data-path-to-node="11,1,1,0" data-index-in-node="77">Google Vision</b> to extract your exact coverages so you compare apples-to-apples.</span></td></tr><tr><td><span data-path-to-node="11,2,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="11,2,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Anonymous Quoter</b></span></td><td><span data-path-to-node="11,2,1,0">Fills out 5-10 carrier sites using a temporary alias.</span></td></tr><tr><td><span data-path-to-node="11,3,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="11,3,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Direct Contact Card</b></span></td><td><span data-path-to-node="11,3,1,0">Instead of "Apply Now," it gives you the <b data-path-to-node="11,3,1,0" data-index-in-node="41">Direct Phone Number</b> of a local independent agent (not a call center) with a pre-written script: <i data-path-to-node="11,3,1,0" data-index-in-node="137">"I am looking for policy #123, I saw a rate of $X online. The "Atlanta Specific" Insight</h3><p data-path-to-node="13">Since you mentioned State Farm and the ability to negotiate, your app should prioritize <b data-path-to-node="13" data-index-in-node="88">Independent Brokers</b>. In 2026, there are many "Insurtech" platforms (like <b data-path-to-node="13" data-index-in-node="161">Tigerlab</b> or <b data-path-to-node="13" data-index-in-node="173">Openkoda</b>) that provide modular APIs. You could build a tool that specifically pings independent agencies in Metro Atlanta‚Äîthese guys represent 20+ companies and usually have much better ethics about not selling your data compared to the "big box" websites.</p><hr data-path-to-node="14"><p data-path-to-node="15"><b data-path-to-node="15" data-index-in-node="0">Would you like me to find the specific API documentation for a service dir="ltr" style="--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-animation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node="0">It is definitely not too complicated, but you‚Äôre running into the <b data-path-to-node="0" data-index-in-node="66">"Lead-Gen Wall."</b> These sites make finding a simple answer hard on purpose because they want to capture your data and sell it.</p><p data-path-to-node="1">To answer your question: <b data-path-to-node="1" data-index-in-node="25">Yes, there is a simple way.</b> If you want to build this for your own use (or as a hackathon MVP), you can create an <b data-path-to-node="1" data-index-in-node="139">Anonymous Estimator</b> that uses public data rather than private quotes.</p><p data-path-to-node="2">Here is how you get the info without the spam:</p><h3 data-path-to-node="3">1. The "Clean" Data Source (Georgia Specific)</h3><p data-path-to-node="4">In Georgia, you don't actually need a quote to find the cheapest company. Because companies must file their rates publicly, we already know who the "price leaders" are for your specific demographic in Atlanta for 2026.</p><p data-path-to-node="5"><b data-path-to-node="5" data-index-in-node="0">For a household with three young drivers in Atlanta, these are the 2026 leaders:</b></p><ul data-path-to-node="6"><li><p data-path-to-node="6,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="6,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Cheapest Overall:</b> <b data-path-to-node="6,0,0" data-index-in-node="18">Georgia Farm Bureau</b> (Average $134/mo for full coverage). They are almost always the lowest for families because they are a non-profit member organization.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="6,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="6,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Best for Teens/Young Drivers:</b> <b data-path-to-node="6,1,0" data-index-in-node="30">Central Insurance</b> or <b data-path-to-node="6,1,0" data-index-in-node="51">Progressive</b>. Progressive‚Äôs algorithm in Georgia currently favors young drivers more than State Farm's does.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="6,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="6,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">The "No-Spam" Alternative:</b> <b data-path-to-node="6,2,0" data-index-in-node="27">Auto-Owners</b>. They don't have a quote button on their site. You <i data-path-to-node="6,2,0" data-index-in-node="90">have</i> to call a local agent. This is the "Gold Standard" for avoiding spam.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="7">2. How your "Simple App" would work</h3><p data-path-to-node="8">If you were to build this at your next hackathon, you could make it a <b data-path-to-node="8" data-index-in-node="70">"Rate Table Lookup"</b> rather than a "Quote Engine."</p><ul data-path-to-node="9"><li><p data-path-to-node="9,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="9,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Input:</b> User enters Age, Gender, Car Make/Model, and Zip Code.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="9,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="9,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Backend:</b> Instead of hitting a "Get Quote" API (which triggers the spam), the app queries a static database of the <b data-path-to-node="9,1,0" data-index-in-node="118">Georgia 2026 Rate Filings</b> (which you can download from the GA Dept of Insurance).</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="9,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="9,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Output:</b> "Based on 2026 filings in Atlanta, <b data-path-to-node="9,2,0" data-index-in-node="47">Georgia Farm Bureau</b> is legally required to charge approximately $X for this profile. Call them at [Number] and ask for the 'New Member Rate'."</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="10">3. The "Direct-Only" List for your Kids</h3><p data-path-to-node="11">Since you have the VINs and the address, skip the comparison sites and call these three directly. You will get a firm answer in 10 minutes with zero follow-up spam from third parties:</p><div class="horizontal-scroll-wrapper"><div class="table-block-component"><response-element class="" ng-version="0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER"><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><table-block _nghost-ng-c366137040="" class="ng-star-inserted"><div _ngcontent-ng-c366137040="" class="table-block has-export-button new-table-style is-at-scroll-start is-at-scroll-end"><div _ngcontent-ng-c366137040="" not-end-of-paragraph="" class="table-content not-end-of-paragraph" jslog="275421;track:impression,attention" data-hveid="0" decode-data-ved="1" data-ved="0CAAQ3ecQahcKEwjj9NWK6_qSAxUAAAAAHQAAAAAQXg"><table data-path-to-node="12"><thead><tr><td><span data-path-to-node="12,0,0,0">Company</span></td><td><span data-path-to-node="12,0,1,0">Why call them?</span></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><span data-path-to-node="12,1,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="12,1,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Georgia Farm Bureau</b></span></td><td><span data-path-to-node="12,1,1,0">Consistently the cheapest in GA for 2026. dir="ltr" style="--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-animation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node="0">Building a tool for personal use and hackathons is a fantastic way to handle this, but you have to be strategic about what data is "publicly scrapeable" versus what is "legally locked down."</p><p data-path-to-node="1">Since you're in the Atlanta area, here is exactly where to start and which parts you should‚Äîand shouldn't‚Äîautomate to keep it simple.</p><h3 data-path-to-node="2">1. The Starting Point: The Scraper</h3><p data-path-to-node="3">You are correct: <b data-path-to-node="3" data-index-in-node="17">Start with the Georgia SERFF portal.</b></p><ul data-path-to-node="4"><li><p data-path-to-node="4,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">The URL:</b> <response-element class="" ng-version="0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER"><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><link-block _nghost-ng-c2835501739="" class="ng-star-inserted"><!----><!----><a _ngcontent-ng-c2835501739="" target="_blank" rel="noopener" externallink="" _nghost-ng-c1538880176="" jslog="197247;track:generic_click,impression,attention;BardVeMetadataKey:[[&quot;r_7814de39831984d8&quot;,&quot;c_c94ae2f94064cb99&quot;,null,&quot;rc_7c9ae26e3cad50b8&quot;,null,null,&quot;en&quot;,null,1,null,null,1,0]]" href="https://filingaccess.serff.com/sfa/home/GA" class="ng-star-inserted" data-hveid="0" decode-data-ved="1" data-ved="0CAAQ_4QMahcKEwjj9NWK6_qSAxUAAAAAHQAAAAAQYA">Georgia SERFF Public Access</a><!----></link-block><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----></response-element></p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="4,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">What to Scrape:</b> Look for <b data-path-to-node="4,1,0" data-index-in-node="25">"Rate/Rule"</b> filings for major carriers (State Farm, Progressive, Auto-Owners, Georgia Farm Bureau).</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="4,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Goal:</b> You aren't looking for a "final price" yet; you are looking for the <b data-path-to-node="4,2,0" data-index-in-node="78">"Rating Factors."</b> * <i data-path-to-node="4,2,0" data-index-in-node="98">Example:</i> You'll find a PDF that says: "Base Rate: $500. Multiplier for 18-year-old male: 2.5x. Discount for Good Student: -15%."</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="4,3,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,3,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Hackathon Build:</b> Use <b data-path-to-node="4,3,0" data-index-in-node="25">Python + Playwright</b> to navigate the SERFF portal. Since most of the data is inside PDFs, use a library like <code data-path-to-node="4,3,0" data-index-in-node="133">PyPDF2</code> or an LLM-based parser to extract the numbers into a clean JSON format.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="5">2. The DMV Reality Check (Avoid the API)</h3><p data-path-to-node="6">You mentioned looking at the DMV to confirm a clean license. <b data-path-to-node="6" data-index-in-node="61">This is where you should stop automating.</b></p><ul data-path-to-node="7"><li><p data-path-to-node="7,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="7,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Problem:</b> Accessing Georgia's Department of Driver Services (DDS) records (MVRs) is strictly protected by the <b data-path-to-node="7,0,0" data-index-in-node="113">Driver‚Äôs Privacy Protection Act (DPPA)</b>. Unless you are a licensed insurance agent or have an enterprise business account with the Georgia Technology Authority (GTA), you cannot programmatically query someone's driving record.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="7,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="7,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Simple Fix:</b> Don't build a DMV connection. Instead, build a <b data-path-to-node="7,1,0" data-index-in-node="63">"Self-Certification Toggle"</b> in your app. The user (you) just clicks: <i data-path-to-node="7,1,0" data-index-in-node="132">[X] No tickets in 3 years.</i> This keeps your app legal and "v1" simple.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="8">3. The "Anonymous Estimator" Logic</h3><p data-path-to-node="9">Since you want to avoid spam, your app shouldn't "talk" to insurance companies at all. It should be a <b data-path-to-node="9" data-index-in-node="102">Calculator</b> that lives entirely on your machine.</p><p data-path-to-node="10"><b data-path-to-node="10" data-index-in-node="0">The Workflow:</b></p><ol start="1" data-path-to-node="11"><li><p data-path-to-node="11,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="11,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Input:</b> You enter your kid's age, gender, and the car's Year/Make/Model/VIN.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="11,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="11,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Lookup:</b> Your app pulls the "Base Rates" you scraped from the Georgia SERFF files.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="11,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="11,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">Calculation:</b> It applies the math found in those filings.</p><ul data-path-to-node="11,2,1"><li><p data-path-to-node="11,2,1,0,0"><i data-path-to-node="11,2,1,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Math:</i> <span class="math-inline" data-math="Base Rate \times Age Factor \times Vehicle Risk Tier - (Good Student Discount)" data-index-in-node="6"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.7667em; dir="ltr" style="--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-animation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node="0">"Vibe Coding" in 2026 is all about <b data-path-to-node="0" data-index-in-node="35">intent over syntax</b>. Since you're working on the "Spam-Free Insurance Scout," your goal is to move from a "vibe" (a conceptual desire) to a "covenant" (a structured, working agreement between you and the AI).</p><p data-path-to-node="1">To crush this at a hackathon, here is how you should structure your <b data-path-to-node="1" data-index-in-node="68">Artifacts</b> and your <b data-path-to-node="1" data-index-in-node="87">Starting Prompt</b>.</p><h3 data-path-to-node="2">1. The Artifacts (The "Covenant")</h3><p data-path-to-node="3">In vibe coding, "Artifacts" are the tangible outputs the AI generates. For your insurance app, you should aim to produce these four specific artifacts:</p><ul data-path-to-node="4"><li><p data-path-to-node="4,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">The System Blueprint (<code data-path-to-node="4,0,0" data-index-in-node="22">architecture.md</code>):</b> A document describing how the app bypasses lead-gen (Local-first data, Python scrapers for SERFF, and LLM-based PDF parsing).</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="4,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Data Schema (<code data-path-to-node="4,1,0" data-index-in-node="17">schema.sql</code> or <code data-path-to-node="4,1,0" data-index-in-node="31">types.ts</code>):</b> A clear definition of what an "Insurance Rating Factor" looks like (e.g., <code data-path-to-node="4,1,0" data-index-in-node="116">zip_code_multiplier</code>, <code data-path-to-node="4,1,0" data-index-in-node="137">teen_driver_surcharge</code>, <code data-path-to-node="4,1,0" data-index-in-node="160">good_student_discount</code>).</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="4,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Scraping Engine (<code data-path-to-node="4,2,0" data-index-in-node="21">engine.py</code>):</b> The functional Playwright or BeautifulSoup script that targets the Georgia SERFF portal.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="4,3,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,3,0" data-index-in-node="0">The "Vibe" UI (<code data-path-to-node="4,3,0" data-index-in-node="15">interface.tsx</code>):</b> A clean, Apple-style dashboard that shows "Target Monthly Price" vs "Market Average" without any "Submit Info" buttons.</p></li></ul><hr data-path-to-node="5"><h3 data-path-to-node="6">2. The Starting Prompt</h3><p data-path-to-node="7">Your starting prompt shouldn't just be "make an insurance app." It needs to set the <b data-path-to-node="7" data-index-in-node="84">technical constraints</b> and the <b data-path-to-node="7" data-index-in-node="114">moral "vibe"</b> (No Spam).</p><p data-path-to-node="8"><b data-path-to-node="8" data-index-in-node="0">Copy/Paste this into your LLM to start:</b></p><blockquote data-path-to-node="9"><p data-path-to-node="9,0">"I want to vibe-code a project called <b data-path-to-node="9,0" data-index-in-node="38">'InsuScout ATL'</b>.</p><p data-path-to-node="9,1"><b data-path-to-node="9,1" data-index-in-node="0">The Vibe:</b> Radical privacy and transparency. No lead-gen, no data-selling, and zero spam. It is a tool for parents in Georgia to find real insurance rates for their kids using public data.</p><p data-path-to-node="9,2"><b data-path-to-node="9,2" data-index-in-node="0">The Stack:</b> Python (FastAPI) for the backend, Next.js + Tailwind for the frontend, and Supabase for storage.</p><p data-path-to-node="9,3"><b data-path-to-node="9,3" data-index-in-node="0">The Mission:</b> &gt; 1. Build a scraper that targets the Georgia SERFF portal to find 'Rate Filing' PDFs.
2. Use an LLM-parser to turn those PDF tables into a 'Rating Factor' JSON.
3. Create a frontend where I enter a VIN and driver age, and it calculates the 'True Rate' based on state filings.</p><p data-path-to-node="9,4"><b data-path-to-node="9,4" data-index-in-node="0">First Task:</b> Can you help me design the <code data-path-to-node="9,4" data-index-in-node="39">architecture.md</code> artifact that explains how we will parse the complex PDF rate tables from the Georgia Department of Insurance without losing data integrity?"</p></blockquote><hr data-path-to-node="10"><h3 data-path-to-node="11">3. <span class="hljs-keyword">async</span> <span class="hljs-function"><span class="hljs-keyword">def</span> <span class="hljs-title">run_scraper</span>():</span>

        )
        page = <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> context.new_page()

        <span class="hljs-comment"># The portal requires you to accept terms before you can see the search fields</span>

            print(<span class="hljs-string">"‚úÖ Agreement Accepted."</span>)

        <span class="hljs-comment"># Step 2: Navigate to Search</span>
        <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> page.wait_for_selector(<span class="hljs-string">"text=Begin Search"</span>)
        <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> page.click(<span class="hljs-string">"text=Begin Search"</span>)

        <span class="hljs-comment"># Step 3: Fill out the Search Form</span>
        <span class="hljs-comment"># 'Property &amp; Casualty' is the Business Type for Auto Insurance</span>
        <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> page.select_option(<span class="hljs-string">"select#businessType"</span>, label=<span class="hljs-string">"Property &amp; Casualty"</span>)
        
        <span class="hljs-comment"># Searching for State Farm (as an example)</span>
        <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> page.fill(<span class="hljs-string">"input#companyName"</span>, <span class="hljs-string">"State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Company"</span>)
        
        <span class="hljs-comment"># Focus on 'Rate' filings</span>
        <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> page.select_option(<span class="hljs-string">"select#filingType"</span>, label=<span class="hljs-string">"Rate/Rule"</span>)

        print(<span class="hljs-string">"üîç Searching for State Farm Rate Filings..."</span>)
        <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> page.click(<span class="hljs-string">"button#search"</span>)

        <span class="hljs-comment"># Step 4: Extract the PDF Links</span>
        <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> page.wait_for_selector(<span class="hljs-string">"table#resultsTable"</span>)
        
        <span class="hljs-comment"># Scrape the first 5 results</span>
        rows = <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> page.query_selector_all(<span class="hljs-string">"table#resultsTable tbody tr"</span>)
        filings = []
        
        <span class="hljs-keyword">for</span> row <span class="hljs-keyword">in</span> rows[:<span class="hljs-number">5</span>]:

                filing_date = <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> cells[<span class="hljs-number">2</span>].inner_text()
                <span class="hljs-comment"># Find the 'View' link which leads to the actual PDF list</span>
                view_link = <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> cells[<span class="hljs-number">0</span>].query_selector(<span class="hljs-string">"a"</span>)
                href = <span class="hljs-keyword">await</span> view_link.get_attribute(<span class="hljs-string">"href"</span>) <span class="hljs-keyword">if</span> view_link <span class="hljs-keyword">else</span> <span class="hljs-literal">None</span>

                    <span class="hljs-string">"date"</span>: filing_date.strip(),
                    <span class="hljs-string">"url"</span>: <span class="hljs-string">f"https://filingaccess.serff.com<span class="hljs-subst">{href}</span>"</span>

<span class="hljs-function"><span class="hljs-keyword">def</span> <span class="hljs-title">parse_insurance_pdf</span>(<span class="hljs-params">pdf_path</span>):</span>
    <span class="hljs-string">"""
    Sends the PDF directly to Gemini-3-Flash for 'Vision-based' table extraction.
    This bypasses traditional text-parsing issues with insurance table layouts.
    """</span>
    print(<span class="hljs-string">f"üìÑ Parsing <span class="hljs-subst">{pdf_path}</span> using Vision LLM..."</span>)
    
    <span class="hljs-keyword">with</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">open</span>(pdf_path, <span class="hljs-string">"rb"</span>) <span class="hljs-keyword">as</span> f:
        pdf_bytes = f.read()

    <span class="hljs-comment"># The 'Prompt' is the Schema</span>
    prompt = <span class="hljs-string">"""
    Extract the insurance rating tables from this document into a structured JSON.
    I need three specific objects:
    1. 'base_rates': The starting annual premium for Atlanta (Zip 30303).
    2. 'driver_multipliers': Multipliers for Age, Gender, and Marital Status.
    3. 'vehicle_symbols': The risk multipliers for common car years/makes/models.

    Format the response as a valid JSON object. If a value is missing, use null.
    """</span>

    response = client.models.generate_content(
        model=<span class="hljs-string">"gemini-3-flash-preview"</span>, <span class="hljs-comment"># Flash is optimized for speed/extraction</span>
        contents=[
            types.Part.from_bytes(data=pdf_bytes, mime_type=<span class="hljs-string">"application/pdf"</span>),
            prompt
        ],
        config=types.GenerateContentConfig(
            response_mime_type=<span class="hljs-string">"application/json"</span>, <span class="hljs-comment"># Forces valid JSON output</span>
        )
    )
    
    <span class="hljs-keyword">return</span> response.text

<span class="hljs-keyword">from</span> google <span class="hljs-keyword">import</span> genai
<span class="hljs-keyword">from</span> google.genai <span class="hljs-keyword">import</span> types

<span class="hljs-comment"># 1. Setup your API Key (Get a free one at aistudio.google.com)</span>
<span class="hljs-comment"># Pro Tip: In a real app, use an .env file for this!</span>
GEMINI_API_KEY = <span class="hljs-string">"YOUR_GEMINI_API_KEY_HERE"</span>
client = genai.Client(api_key=GEMINI_API_KEY)

<span class="hljs-function"><span class="hljs-keyword">def</span> <span class="hljs-title">parse_insurance_pdf</span>(<span class="hljs-params">pdf_path</span>):</span>
    <span class="hljs-string">"""
    Uses Gemini's Vision capabilities to extract complex 
    insurance rate tables into a clean JSON format.
    """</span>
    print(<span class="hljs-string">f"üëÅÔ∏è  Analyzing PDF: <span class="hljs-subst">{pdf_path}</span>"</span>)
    
    <span class="hljs-keyword">with</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">open</span>(pdf_path, <span class="hljs-string">"rb"</span>) <span class="hljs-keyword">as</span> f:
        pdf_bytes = f.read()

    <span class="hljs-comment"># We provide a strict 'Covenant' (the Prompt) to ensure zero hallucination</span>
    prompt = <span class="hljs-string">"""
    Extract the following data from this Georgia insurance rate filing PDF.
    Output ONLY valid JSON in this exact structure:
    {
      "carrier": "string",
      "effective_date": "string",
      "base_rate_atlanta": number,
      "multipliers": {
        "teen_male": number,
        "teen_female": number,
        "good_student_discount": number
      },
      "vehicle_risk_symbols": [
        {"make": "string", "model": "string", "symbol": number}
      ]
    }
    Scan the tables specifically for the 'Rating Factors' and 'Base Premium' sections.
    """</span>

    response = client.models.generate_content(
        model=<span class="hljs-string">"gemini-3-flash-preview"</span>, 
        contents=[
            types.Part.from_bytes(data=pdf_bytes, mime_type=<span class="hljs-string">"application/pdf"</span>),
            prompt
        ],
        config=types.GenerateContentConfig(
            response_mime_type=<span class="hljs-string">"application/json"</span>,
        )
    )
    
    <span class="hljs-keyword">return</span> response.text

<span class="hljs-keyword">if</span> __name__ == <span class="hljs-string">"__main__"</span>:
    <span class="hljs-comment"># Test this by pointing it to a PDF you downloaded with engine.py</span>

model: raptor-mini # Using the code-optimized model we discussed
tools:
<span class="hljs-bullet">  -</span> #tool:githubRepo

<span class="hljs-section"># Instructions</span>
You are the lead developer for InsuScout ATL. Your primary directive is to find insurance data WITHOUT triggering lead-gen spam.

<span class="hljs-section">## Your Rules:</span>
<span class="hljs-bullet">1.</span> <span class="hljs-strong">**Source of Truth:**</span> Always prioritize data from <span class="hljs-code">`engine.py`</span> (scraped SERFF data) and <span class="hljs-code">`parser.py`</span> (parsed PDF JSON).
<span class="hljs-bullet">2.</span> <span class="hljs-strong">**Privacy First:**</span> Never suggest using an API that requires a user's phone number or email unless it's a "Burner" service.
<span class="hljs-bullet">3.</span> <span class="hljs-strong">**Local First:**</span> Keep all rating logic in <span class="hljs-code">`calculator.py`</span>. 
<span class="hljs-bullet">4.</span> <span class="hljs-strong">**Code Style:**</span> Use FastAPI for backend and shadcn/ui for the dashboard.

<span class="hljs-section">## Your Skills:</span>
<span class="hljs-bullet">-</span> When asked to "find rates," run the <span class="hljs-code">`engine.py`</span> script and report findings.
<span class="hljs-bullet">-</span> When asked to "calculate," use the logic in <span class="hljs-code">`calculator.py`</span> with the latest JSON data.

Choosing the right folder determines how "portable" your agent is and which AI "engine" powers its brain.</p><h3 data-path-to-node="1">Which one should you choose?</h3><p data-path-to-node="2">For your <b data-path-to-node="2" data-index-in-node="9">InsuScout ATL</b> project, here is the breakdown:</p><ul data-path-to-node="3"><li><p data-path-to-node="3,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="3,0,0" data-index-in-node="0"><code data-path-to-node="3,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">.github\agents</code> (The Winner):</b> Use this for <b data-path-to-node="3,0,0" data-index-in-node="42">Workspace-specific agents</b>. This is where you save <code data-path-to-node="3,0,0" data-index-in-node="92">.agent.md</code> files that are committed to your repo. It‚Äôs perfect for a hackathon because if you share the code, the agent and its "persona" go with it.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="3,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="3,1,0" data-index-in-node="0"><code data-path-to-node="3,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">.claude\agents</code>:</b> Use this if you want to use <b data-path-to-node="3,1,0" data-index-in-node="44">Claude-specific agents</b> or local sub-agents. It supports Claude‚Äôs specific agent harness and tools, which is great if you prefer the Anthropic "vibe" for planning.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="3,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="3,2,0" data-index-in-node="0"><code data-path-to-node="3,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">User Data</code>:</b> Use this for <b data-path-to-node="3,2,0" data-index-in-node="24">Global agents</b>. These stay in your personal VS Code profile and work across <i data-path-to-node="3,2,0" data-index-in-node="99">all</i> your projects. 2026, naming your custom agent in VS Code is more than just a label‚Äîit's the <b data-path-to-node="0" data-index-in-node="80">identifier</b> you'll use to summon it in chat. Since your project is "InsuScout ATL," you want a name that is short, descriptive, and easy to type.</p><h3 data-path-to-node="1">1. Naming Guidelines for 2026</h3><p data-path-to-node="2">When the "Configure Custom Agents" menu asks for a name, keep these rules in mind:</p><ul data-path-to-node="3"><li><p data-path-to-node="3,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="3,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Characters:</b> You can only use letters (a-z, A-Z), numbers (0-9), dots (.), hyphens (-), and underscores (_).</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="3,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="3,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Case Sensitivity:</b> Most developers prefer <b data-path-to-node="3,1,0" data-index-in-node="41">PascalCase</b> (e.g., <code data-path-to-node="3,1,0" data-index-in-node="59">InsuScout</code>) or <b data-path-to-node="3,1,0" data-index-in-node="73">kebab-case</b> (e.g., <code data-path-to-node="3,1,0" data-index-in-node="91">insu-scout</code>) for easy recognition.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="3,2,0"><b data-path-to-node="3,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">The Suffix:</b> You don't need to add ".agent" to the name field; VS Code will automatically associate it with your <code data-path-to-node="3,2,0" data-index-in-node="112">.agent.md</code> file.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="4">2. Recommended Names for Your Project</h3><p data-path-to-node="5">Choose one of these based on how you want to interact with it:</p><ul data-path-to-node="6"><li><p data-path-to-node="6,0,0"><code data-path-to-node="6,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">InsuScout</code>: Clean and professional.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="6,1,0"><code data-path-to-node="6,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">RateScout</code>: Focuses on the "Scraping" aspect.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="6,2,0"><code data-path-to-node="6,2,0" data-index-in-node="0">AgentATL</code>: Good if you plan to build other regional versions later.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="7">3. How to Set the Name</h3><p data-path-to-node="8">Once you've chosen a name, you actually define it in <b data-path-to-node="8" data-index-in-node="53">two places</b> within your project:</p><p data-path-to-node="9"><b data-path-to-node="9" data-index-in-node="0">A. The Filename (The Identity)</b>
When you click "Create new custom agent," name the file <code data-path-to-node="9" data-index-in-node="87">insu-scout.agent.md</code>. This is what shows up in your file explorer.</p><p data-path-to-node="10"><b data-path-to-node="10" data-index-in-node="0">B. The YAML Frontmatter (The Display Name)</b>
Inside that file, the <code data-path-to-node="10" data-index-in-node="65">name</code> field is what actually appears in the VS Code chat dropdown. _ngcontent-ng-c2203757349="" role="text" data-test-id="code-content" class="code-container formatted ng-tns-c2203757349-201"><span class="hljs-section"># Role &amp; Mission</span>
You are the <span class="hljs-strong">**InsuScout ATL Expert**</span>. Your mission is to provide radical transparency into the Georgia auto insurance market. You help parents find the "True Rate" for their children by bypassing marketing sites and going directly to state-filed public data.

<span class="hljs-section"># Operational Procedures</span>
<span class="hljs-bullet">1.</span> <span class="hljs-strong">**Search &amp; Scrape:**</span> When asked for rates, use the <span class="hljs-code">`execute`</span> tool to run <span class="hljs-code">`python engine.py`</span>. Search only for official "Rate/Rule" filings on the Georgia SERFF portal.
<span class="hljs-bullet">2.</span> <span class="hljs-strong">**Data Extraction:**</span> Use <span class="hljs-code">`parser.py`</span> to convert downloaded PDFs into JSON. Never ask the user to manually type in data that can be scraped.
<span class="hljs-bullet">3.</span> <span class="hljs-strong">**Calculation:**</span> Use <span class="hljs-code">`calculator.py`</span> to apply the Georgia-specific multipliers (Age, Zip Code, Safety Symbols).
<span class="hljs-bullet">4.</span> <span class="hljs-strong">**The "No-Spam" Guardrail:**</span> If a task requires a user's phone number or email, STOP. Inform the user that this violates the "No-Spam" policy of the project. Suggest using an anonymous lookup instead.

<span class="hljs-section"># Knowledge Base</span>
<span class="hljs-bullet">-</span> You are an expert on <span class="hljs-strong">**Georgia Code Title 33**</span> (Insurance).
<span class="hljs-bullet">-</span> You know that <span class="hljs-strong">**Georgia Farm Bureau**</span> and <span class="hljs-strong">**Auto-Owners**</span> are often the price leaders for teen drivers in 2026.
<span class="hljs-bullet">-</span> You understand <span class="hljs-strong">**VIN Decoding**</span> and how safety features (lane assist, etc.) impact insurance symbols.

<span class="hljs-section"># Feedback Loop</span>
After every calculation, provide a "Talking Points" list that the user can take to an independent agent to ensure they get every legal discount found in the filings.
</code></pre><!----></div></div></div><!----><!----></code-block><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----></response-element><h3 data-path-to-node="8">3. </h2><!----><!----><structured-content-container _ngcontent-ng-c3463365586="" class="model-response-text is-mobile processing-state-visible ng-star-inserted" _nghost-ng-c544387144="" style="height: auto;"><div _ngcontent-ng-c544387144="" class="container"><message-content _ngcontent-ng-c544387144="" _nghost-ng-c129479174="" id="message-content-id-r_528a9bfbeed8365e" class="ng-star-inserted"><div id="model-response-message-contentr_528a9bfbeed8365e" aria-live="off" aria-busy="false" dir="ltr" style="--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-animation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node="0">In 2026, the <b data-path-to-node="0" data-index-in-node="13">"Command + S"</b> behavior in VS Code has been updated to treat AI instructions just like source code. When you hit Save, it wants to store your agent‚Äôs "brain" on your hard drive so that the configuration becomes a permanent part of your project.</p><p data-path-to-node="1">Here is why it's asking and exactly where to save it to keep the "vibe" alive:</p><h3 data-path-to-node="2">1. Why it's saving to your Hard Drive</h3><p data-path-to-node="3">Unlike a typical chat with a bot, a <b data-path-to-node="3" data-index-in-node="36">Custom Agent</b> is a file-based configuration. For the <code data-path-to-node="3" data-index-in-node="88">@insu-scout</code> agent to work, VS Code needs to read that <code data-path-to-node="3" data-index-in-node="142">.agent.md</code> file every time you open the project.</p><ul data-path-to-node="4"><li><p data-path-to-node="4,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Version Control:</b> By saving it to your hard drive (in your project folder), you can commit it to Git. This means if you work on a different computer tomorrow, your custom agent will be right there waiting for you.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="4,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="4,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Auto-Discovery:</b> VS Code looks at specific folders on your drive to "discover" which agents are available.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="5">2. The "Correct" Location</h3><p data-path-to-node="6">When the save dialog pops up, ensure you are saving it here:</p><blockquote data-path-to-node="7"><p data-path-to-node="7,0"><code data-path-to-node="7,0" data-index-in-node="0">Your-Project-Folder/.github/agents/insu-scout.agent.md</code></p></blockquote><p data-path-to-node="8"><b data-path-to-node="8" data-index-in-node="0">Note:</b> If the <code data-path-to-node="8" data-index-in-node="13">.github/agents</code> folder doesn't exist, you can create it right inside the save window. This is the "Standard Workspace" location for 2026.</p><h3 data-path-to-node="9">3. What if you don't want it in your project?</h3><p data-path-to-node="10">If you want this agent to follow you to <i data-path-to-node="10" data-index-in-node="40">every</i> project you ever work on (Personal, Work, Hackathons), you can save it to your <b data-path-to-node="10" data-index-in-node="125">User Profile</b> instead.</p><ul data-path-to-node="11"><li><p data-path-to-node="11,0,0">To do this, go back to the <b data-path-to-node="11,0,0" data-index-in-node="27">Configure Custom Agents</b> menu and select <b data-path-to-node="11,0,0" data-index-in-node="67">"User Profile"</b> as the location.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="11,1,0">VS Code will then save it in a hidden global folder on your drive (e.g., <code data-path-to-node="11,1,0" data-index-in-node="73">%AppData%\Code\User\prompts</code> on Windows), and you won't see it in your project sidebar.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node="12">4. The "Standard Save" Workflow</h3><p data-path-to-node="13">Once you save the file once:</p><ol start="1" data-path-to-node="14"><li><p data-path-to-node="14,0,0"><b data-path-to-node="14,0,0" data-index-in-node="0">Hit <code data-path-to-node="14,0,0" data-index-in-node="4">Cmd + S</code></b> anytime you change the instructions.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node="14,1,0"><b data-path-to-node="14,1,0" data-index-in-node="0">Look for the Refresh icon</b> in the Copilot Chat. Usually, VS Code will live-reload the agent, but sometimes you might need to click the "Refresh" button in the agent picker to apply your new "No-Spam" rules.</p></li></ol><p data-path-to-node="15"><b data-path-to-node="15" data-index-in-node="0">Would you like me to help you check if your <code data-path-to-node="15" data-index-in-node="44">.gitignore</code> file is blocking this folder, so your agent doesn't get left behind when you push to GitHub?</b></p><hr data-path-to-node="16"><p data-path-to-node="17"><response-element class="" ng-version="0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER"><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><link-block _nghost-ng-c2835501739="" class="ng-star-inserted"><!----><!----><a _ngcontent-ng-c2835501739="" target="_blank" rel="noopener" externallink="" _nghost-ng-c1538880176="" jslog="197247;track:generic_click,impression,attention;BardVeMetadataKey:[[&quot;r_528a9bfbeed8365e&quot;,&quot;c_c94ae2f94064cb99&quot;,null,&quot;rc_7bb6c5f15597eb15&quot;,null,null,&quot;en&quot;,null,1,null,null,1,0]]" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XqaqBmeMVvk" class="ng-star-inserted" data-hveid="0" decode-data-ved="1" data-ved="0CAAQ_4QMahgKEwjj9NWK6_qSAxUAAAAAHQAAAAAQ0AM">VS Code Workspace vs User Settings</a><!----></link-block><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----></response-element>
